review_blob: Pours reddish-brown with a thin tan head.  Lots of particles floating around.  Aroma is roasty, caramel, a bit musty.  Taste is moderately sweet at first, followed by a mild bitterness.  Finish is moderate, with a good sweet/bitter balance.  Overall pretty good.

12 oz bottle.  Pours Amber with moderate head.  Balanced aroma - hoppy at first, but a bit of sweet caramel maltiness as well.  Taste is fairly bitter.  Also has a bit of sweetness at the front of the tongue, but it is overwhelmed by lingering bitterness at the back.  Lingering bitter finish.  Overall not bad, but would have wanted a bit more balance.

12 oz bottle.  Pours amber with thin tan head.  Aroma is strong and sweet - exactly like pumpkin pie.  Taste is quite sweet and subtle as well, with the pumpkin and spice flavours coming through.  Slight bitterness at the finish, but sweetness is more prevalent.  This is a really nice fall beer.

12oz bottle.  Pours a slightly cloudy amber with moderate tan head.  Aroma is initially a bit sour and yeasty, with a more subtle caramel aroma later.  Taste is quite bland, not much there - a bit of sweetness, but just barely.  There just isnt much here - I was expecting a lot more.

12 oz bottle.  Pours a dark brown with a thin tan head.  Aroma of chocolate, roasted coffee and caramel, a bit of yeastiness.  Taste is surprisingly sweet, with a light coffee bitterness on the tip of the tongue.  Moderate carbonation with a creamy texture.  Lasting finish.  A good beer to prepare for winter.

Pours an amber with a nice moderately foamy head.  Aroma of caramel malts.  Taste is really nice - moderate but delicate sweetness with a tiny bit of bitterness.  Finish is clean, no surprises on the palate.  Overall this is very pleasant to drink.

750 mL bottle.  Pours a near-black with tan head.  Aroma is of chocolate, coffee, toast, and more chocolate.  Taste has bit of sweetness up front followed by significant coffee/espresso bitterness.  Long, bitter finish.

Large bottle.  Pours slightly hazy copper colour.  Moderate head.  Aroma is fairly hoppy, with the spruce barrels coming through a bit.  Alcohol hits you at first taste - this is where the juniper berries and gin barrels come through.  A bit of sweetness follows, with a final long bitter finish at the back and side of the mouth.  This one is pretty good - unique.

12 oz bottle.  Pours a brown with moderate, quickly diminishing tan head.  Sweet caremel/chocolate malt aroma, with hint of licorice?  Taste is pretty nice.  Initially a bit sour moving to moderate sweetness and then with a light bitterness towards the end.  Comes across as reasonably light tasting for a brown ale, but not in bad way.  Overall pretty good.

Large bottle.  Pours a hazy light orange with relatively thin white head.  Aroma is fresh and hoppy.  Some citrusy fruits on the nose, including apricots.  Taste is mild sweetness with some of the fruitiness coming through.  Frothy carbonation, alcohol content comes through on initial sip but is significantly muted afterwards.  Subtle finish.

12 oz bottle.  Pours an amber with thin off-white head.  Aroma is toasty, with a bit of caramel and a tiny bit of yeastiness.  Taste is moderately bitter, receding into a mildly sweet refreshing finish.  This one isnt remarkably unique, but a very solid basic beer.

650 mL bottle.  Pours cloudy pale straw colour.  Aroma is fairly hoppy with a bit of sweetness.  Taste is surprisingly sweet, the honey coming through.  Not much fruit or tartness though.  Not overly complex.  Moderate carbonation, relatively clean and short finish.  Pretty good.

Pours a dark cloudy amber-brown.  Aroma is citrusy with some fruity tartness - reminds me of pressed apples.  Taste is very powerful and complex, tons of flavours mixing together.  Initial reaction is of peppery alcohol, but quickly mellows into a bitter smooth lingering.  Palate feels a bit heavy on carbonation - foamy.  Finish is long and warming.

12 oz bottle.  Pours a clear amber.  Little lacing of white head.  Aroma is bready with a bit of honey and almond sweetness.  Taste starts with light sourness, with medium bitterness following.  Texture is quite thick with a long bitter finish.  Overall pretty good but not my favorite of the Brooklyn beers.

500 mL bottle.  Pours a reddish amber with a moderate head.  Aroma is great - a bit of light fruity (bubblegum?) sweetness but with a significant toasty maltiness underlying.  Taste is initially sweet, until the bitterness of the malts comes through.  Finish is bitter, with a bit of spiciness.  Overall pretty nice - an interesting balance between sweetness and toasty bitterness.

355 mL bottle.  Pours a dark caramel colour.  Minimal head.  Aroma is surprisingly faint and lacks a bit of the buttery sweetness of the normal Innis & Gunn - what is there is more of a darker caramel or molasses aroma.  Taste is quite nice and sweet, followed by the spiciness of the alcohol.  Mouthfeel is moderate - reasonably lively carbonation with a moderately long sweet finish.  Not too bad, but frankly prefer the normal Innis & Gunn.
beer_name: Innis & Gunn Canadian Cask Oak Aged Beer

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: 500 mL bottle.  Pours a very cloudy light amber - some sediment floating around.  Aroma is absolutely fantastic.  Ripe fruits - apricots and plum, along with some light floral hops.  Alcohol comes through in strength on first taste but quickly recedes into a slightly bitter but mostly sweet taste.  Very full-bodied, feels almost syrupy in the mouth.  An interesting and fantastic beer.

Pours a very pale straw colour with minimal head.  Aroma is light and fresh, mildly hoppy.  Taste is mildly bitter, with a bit of lingering sweetness.  Finish is fairly short.  Overall, this is a pretty basic beer, really nothing special about it.

Pours a surprisingly cloudy reddish-rose with minimal head.  Fruity aroma - apricots, raspberry.  Taste is surprisingly bitter with a sour fruity tinge.  Long dry, bitter tannin-like finish.  Overall, this is surprising in every way.  Truly unique, like nothing I have ever had before.  Wouldnt recommend this for a session, but great for a try.

341 mL bottle.  Pours a pale straw colour with moderate head.  Aroma is, as the label would suggest, of blueberries.  Other milder sweet fruit aromas coming through as well.  Taste is light with a hint of sourness fading into sweetness.  Fairly lively with a reasonably long finish.  Overall this is a great summer beer - very subtle easy to drink.

500 mL bottle.  Pours a light amber with moderate frothy head.  Aroma of citrus and a bit of yeast.  Taste is surprisingly bitter for a lager - it lasts well after drinking.  Nothing too complex in the palate, but a fairly solid simple beer.

Pours an orangey-amber with a slight head.  Light aroma of autumn spices.  Taste is moderately bitter, moving to a sweeter finish.  Alcohol content provides some warmth initially, but mouthfeel is a bit thin after that wears off.  Overall, not bad, but left me hoping for a bit more.

Pours a clear, light amber with moderate white foamy head.  Aroma is a bit skunky at first, then yields to sweet hops.  Taste is a bit metallic with a lingering sweetness.  Lively on the palate.  Overall would be refreshing if youre out on the patio having a drink - wouldnt recommend as an evening or session beer though.

Pours a cloudy straw colour with a thick foamy head.  Aroma is citrus and sprucey, like I would expect from Belgian Strong Ale.  Taste is light and refreshing - mild sweetness and a bit of a bitter finish.  Palate is great - lively and fine carbonation makes this feel like drinking champagne.  Overall quite nice.

Pours a pale, cloudy straw.  Aroma is a bit skunky at first, but soon yields to some mild hops.  Strong alcohol taste at first, followed by a mild sweetness, then a lasting bitterness.  High alcohol content gives this a very warming mouthfeel.  Bitterness creates a bit of an anise finish.  Overall interesting, but not particularly my style.
500 mL bottle.  Pours a clear amber with mildly frothy off-white head.  Aroma is... not great.  A bit mildewy and skunky.  Pleasantly bitter taste but without much finish.  Creamy on the palate.

500 mL bottle.  Pours dark ruby-amber, little to no head.  Aroma is a bit malty (caramel, oats) but with a fruity sweetness as well.  Taste is of moderate fruity sweetness which fades into a light roasty bitterness.  Alcohol hits the palate strongly at first sip, but is barely noticeable afterwards.  Full body with a lasting finish.  Quite nice - very refreshing for a stronger beer.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: 500 mL bottle.  Purchased this by accident thinking it was the normal Aventinus.  Pours a cloudy, slightly syrupy brown.  Aroma is of malt and fruits - banana and strawberry.  A bit of a burnt sugar aroma as well.  Taste is powerful - starts off sweet, then the high alcohol content reaches the nostrils.  Aftertaste is of lingering sweetness.  Body is full, with moderate carbonation and a slightly syrupy texture.  Very nice overall.

650 mL bottle.  Pours a cloudy amber with moderate head.  Aroma is extremely hoppy, strong citrus notes (orange/pineapple).  Taste is slightly sweet moving to a strong bitter.  Moderate carbonation, full body, long bitter finish.  Really like this one.

Pours a pale straw colour with a moderately thick white head.  Aroma is quite hoppy, with a little bit of sweet citrus fruit.  Taste is fantastic.  Mildly sweet moving to a slightly bitter finish.  Medium body with a very clean texture and finish.  Overall, not a particularly complex beer, but it executes on the Pilsener style perfectly.

Pours pale golden with light head.  Aroma is a bit skunky at first, with a light butterscotch/oak aroma afterwards that is lighter than the normal Innis & Gunn.  Taste is mildly sweet, with a bit of lingering bitterness towards the end.  Quite heavy on the carbonation, bit of a thin texture.  Overall its pretty good, but I certainly prefer the regular oak aged beer

Pours hazy orange with a off-white head that quickly dissipates.  Aroma is fantastic.  Mellow sweet fruitiness (apricots and maybe coconut??), with a bit of spicy and bready nose.  Taste is very sweet - spiciness kicks in after a few seconds but subsides again to a bit of a malty sweetness.  Thick, almost syrupy texture, very rich.  Not much carbonation.  Long finish.  Fantastic.

Pours a cloudy light brown with a thick foamy off-white head.  Aroma is earthy and bready with some light maltiness.  Taste is surprisingly light and initially a bit sweet, with a bit of banana, cloves - finishes slightly bitter.  Moderate to lively carbonation with a bit of a thin texture.  Overall pretty nice

Pours clear golden with moderate white head.  Aroma is a bit hoppy, with citrus notes (bit of tangerine?).  Taste is moderately bitter, but not particularly complex.  Palate is a bit thin with a fairly short finish.  Overall nothing great - better than the macro lagers, but nothing really stands out for this beer.  Given the name I would have expected a bit more unique hoppiness.

Pours black with a thin tan head.  Aroma is bready toasty malts.  Taste is a bit of molasses sweetness from the malts, with a slightly bitter finish.  Carbonation is moderate, with a dry finish.  Overall pretty good, but nothing outstanding

Pours a cloudy reddish-orange.  Aroma is of sweet fruits - taste has a bit of tartness, but not nearly as sour as I was expecting.  Cranberry comes through a bit on the taste, but not overpowering - other fruitiness comes through as well.  Overall quite nice.
Pours a hazy amber.  Aroma is rich, floral and a bit fruity (melon?).  Taste is quite bitter, with a dry finish.  Lively on the palate.  Overall quite nice - very flavourful.

Pours a dark brown with a thin tan head.  Aroma is rich and sweet, with espresso, chocolate, caramel, maple notes.  Taste is slightly bitter to begin, then moves to a sweeter dark chocolate taste and finishes with an espresso taste.  Great progression.  Overall a really nice porter.

Pours a clear amber with a moderate tan head.  Aroma is malty, grainy with a bit of mustiness.  Taste is a bit bitter, but not overpowering.  Moderate to heavy carbonation leads to a clean finish.  Overall pretty good.

Pours a pale golden colour with thin white head.  Aroma is of light hops and grains.  Taste is a bit bitter, but overall not much there.  Medium carbonation and a bit of a dry finish.  Overall nothing spectacular.
341mL bottle.  Pours a clear brown with fine tan head.  Aroma is malty with dark fruits.  Aroma is full and refreshing, with sweetness shifting to a bitter finish.  Overall very nice.

355 mL bottle - pours a hazy red with a moderate creme head.  Aroma is light and hoppy, with a bit of tart fruitiness.  Flavour is rich and a bit tart - bitter spiciness at the finish.  Heavy on carbonation.  Overall pretty nic.

500 mL bottle.  Pours clear golden straw colour with quickly dissipating head.  Aroma is a bit skunky at first, light yeast and hops as well.  Flavour is pretty basic, medium bitterness with the yeasty taste coming through.  Palate is clean.  Overall nothing special, and the skunkiness/yeastiness were definitely a put-off - could have been a bad bottle though.

330 mL bottle.  Pours a cloudy golden-white oclour with a frothy white head.  Aroma is mildly hoppy, with citrus and clove notes.  Flavour is spicy with a peppery finish.  Heavy carbonation, but works well with the style.  Overall pretty nice, but nothing outstanding.
Pours a hazy brown with moderate white foamy head - aroma is sweet and hoppy.  Flavour is quite nice - hoppiness continues with a bit of a caramel taste.  Overall very nice
355ml bottle.  Pours a hazy golden with a foamy white head.  Aroma is earthy and a bit yeasty.  Flavour is light and subtle, bit of a light sweetness with the yeasty finish.  Overall pretty nice.

Pours a hazy golden white.  Aroma is a typical weissbier aroma - sweet, spicy and floral, with a bit of bubblegum.  Flavour is subtle and refreshing, with the sweetness and bubblegum coming through again.  Palate is clean with a good amount of carbonation.  Overall quite nice.

650mL bottle.  Pours clear golden-amber with quickly dissipating head.  Light hoppy aroma with slight element of citrus - no overpowering orange aroma.  Flavour is quite bitter - more peel elements than orange.  Finish is clean with a bit of lingering bitterness.  Overall a bit different than expected - not quite as refreshing or fruity as I would have hoped.
beer_name: Great Lakes Brewing Orange Peel Ale

review_blob: 341 mL bottle.  Pours amber with very little head.  Aroma is a bit roasty and earthy.  Flavour starts with a bitter coffee and then turns a bit sour - finishes long and bitter.  Not bad, but I was expecting quite a bit more given the high ratings frankly.
beer_name: Scotch Irish Corporal Punishment (Corporals Bitter Brown)

review_blob: 250mL bottle.  Pours a golden colour with minimal head - aroma is of artificial pineapple, as well as of ripe bananas?  Flavour is tart - fruitiness is present, but not overwhelming.  Finish is relatively clean, but leaves a bit of a sourish taste.  Overall not horrible, but not the best lambic that Ive had.
